For the primary outcome, A1c, there was a trend toward a significant difference between the 2 study groups (P = .0757) with a mean absolute decrease of 0.50% (CI: 0.20%, 0.80%, P = .0008) in the intervention group compared to a decrease of 0.17% (CI: â0.26%, 0.59%, P = .4641) in the control group (Figure 1
, Table 2
). Differences between the 2 study groups for changes from baseline in all other laboratory tests (total, LDL, and HDL cholesterol; total-to-HDL ratio; triglycerides; and fasting blood sugar) were not statistically significant (P > .10). There was a statistically significant decrease in HDL cholesterol over the study period for both the intervention (P < .0001) and the control group (P = .0469). HDL cholesterol declined 6.28 mg/dL (CI: 3.42, 9.13) in the intervention group and 3.62 mg/dL (CI: 0.05, 7.19) in the control group. There were no significant changes from baseline for the other laboratory tests. For systolic and diastolic blood pressure, weight, waist circumference, and BMI, there were no significant changes from baseline and no significant differences between the groups.
